forecast.review: Both forecasters reinforce the core inertia argument. Forecaster 2 adds concrete procedural constraints (GSA domain process, NARA record-retention) and a relevant 2017 precedent of redirects/static pages instead of removal—useful nuance I hadn’t explicitly cited. Forecaster 3 emphasizes stakeholder integration and logistical complexity, which supports persistence but is somewhat overlapping with my prior reasoning. Both also flag small technical/measurement risks (DNS/cert issues), aligning with my earlier outage caveat. I find F2’s procedural specifics most persuasive and incrementally supportive of a higher probability; nothing presented makes me more pessimistic.
forecast.rationale: Time to resolution is short (~48 days). The site is currently up, and elimination of the program doesn’t necessitate immediate domain takedown. Federal web decommissioning typically requires coordination with GSA and adherence to NARA obligations, making a formal shutdown in under two months unlikely. Precedent suggests content deprecation or redirects rather than hard removal. Even a static archive or redirect would register as “up” for the resolution source. Remaining risks: a politically driven symbolic takedown (non-zero but atypical for a long-standing, consumer-facing brand), and small measurement/transient outage risk at the moment of Metaculus’s check. Given the added weight from F2 on GSA/NARA processes, I slightly raise my forecast while keeping a few points for intentional takedown and monitoring risk.
